# Spring Boot stack

- Write clean, documented Java with accurate **Spring Boot** patterns. Layer apps consistently: **controllers**, **services**, **repositories**, **models (entities/DTOs)**, **configuration**.
- **Naming**: PascalCase classes (`UserController`, `OrderService`); camelCase methods/variables (`findUserById`, `isOrderValid`); `ALL_CAPS` constants (`MAX_RETRY_ATTEMPTS`, `DEFAULT_PAGE_SIZE`).
- Prefer **Java 17+** features when they help (records, sealed classes, pattern matching).
- Use **Lombok** to cut boilerplate; pair it with Spring patterns below (constructor injection via `@RequiredArgsConstructor`, logging via `@Slf4j`, etc.).
- Design **REST** APIs with correct HTTP methods and status codes; keep controllers thin and delegate to services.

## Spring Boot core

- Use **Spring Boot starters** and the **dependency BOM** for consistent versions; rely on **auto-configuration** where it fits, and override explicitly when behavior must be guaranteed.
- Use annotations idiomatically: `@SpringBootApplication`, `@RestController`, `@Service`, `@Repository`, `@Configuration`, `@Bean` as appropriate.
- Centralize HTTP/API errors with **`@ControllerAdvice`** + **`@ExceptionHandler`**; return consistent problem bodies and status codes.

## Configuration

- Use **`application.properties`** or **`application.yml`**; split environments with **Spring Profiles** (`dev`, `test`, `prod`).
- Prefer **`@ConfigurationProperties`** for typed, validated config (constructor binding when possible).

## Dependency injection

- Prefer **constructor injection** over field injection for testability and clear dependencies.
- With **Lombok**, use **`@RequiredArgsConstructor`** on classes whose dependencies are `final` fields—Spring injects via the generated constructor; do not mix `@Autowired` on fields.

```java
// Prefer (Lombok + constructor injection)
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class OrderService {
  private final OrderRepository orders;
}

// Acceptable without Lombok
@Service
public class OrderService {
  private final OrderRepository orders;
  public OrderService(OrderRepository orders) { this.orders = orders; }
}

// Avoid for production services
@Service
public class BadOrderService {
  @Autowired
  private OrderRepository orders;
}
```

## Lombok

- Add **`lombok`** as a provided/compile-only dependency; ensure the IDE and annotation processing are enabled so generated code is visible to Spring and tests.
- **`@RequiredArgsConstructor`**: services, controllers, and other Spring components with `final` dependencies (preferred over hand-written constructors).
- **`@Slf4j`**: default logging on classes that log; still use **SLF4J** levels and messages deliberately (replaces manual `Logger` fields).
- **Entities / JPA**: prefer explicit **`@Getter`**, **`@Setter`**, **`@NoArgsConstructor`**, **`@AllArgsConstructor`** (or **`@Data`** only when appropriate); avoid **`@EqualsAndHashCode`** on entities with lazy collections unless you exclude those fields (`@EqualsAndHashCode.Exclude` / `callSuper`).
- **DTOs / API models**: **`@Value`** or **`@Builder`** + **`@Getter`** as needed; use **`@Builder`** for complex immutable DTOs.
- **`@ConfigurationProperties`**: use immutable constructor-bound beans or **records** per Spring Boot 3; add Lombok only where it aligns with Spring’s binding (avoid fighting validation or nested property maps).
- Do not use Lombok to hide side effects or to replace clear business logic; use it for repetitive structure only.

## Data & validation

- Use **Spring Data JPA** when relational persistence fits; model relationships and cascades explicitly; add **Flyway** or **Liquibase** for migrations when schemas evolve.
- Validate input with **Bean Validation** (`@Valid`, `@NotNull`, etc.) and custom validators when rules go beyond annotations.

## Testing

- **JUnit 5** everywhere; **`@SpringBootTest`** for full context integration tests; **`MockMvc`** (or `WebTestClient` for WebFlux) for web layer; **`@DataJpaTest`** for persistence slice tests; use mocks (`@MockBean`) to isolate layers in integration tests.

## Performance & async

- Use **Spring Cache** abstraction when caching helps; tune DB indexes and queries.
- Use **`@Async`** for fire-and-forget or async workflows where appropriate; use **Spring WebFlux** only when reactive stack is a deliberate choice.

## Security

- Use **Spring Security** for authentication/authorization; hash passwords with **BCrypt** (or stronger algorithms aligned with your security policy); configure **CORS** when browsers call the API from other origins.

## Logging & ops

- Log with **SLF4J** and **Logback** (Spring Boot default); use **ERROR / WARN / INFO / DEBUG** deliberately.
- Expose health and metrics via **Spring Boot Actuator** where operations need them.

## API docs

- Document REST APIs with **Springdoc OpenAPI** (OpenAPI 3) on controllers/DTOs.

## Build & deployment

- Use **Maven** (or Gradle) with Spring Boot plugin; environment-specific behavior via **profiles** and externalized config; **Docker** when deploying as containers.

## Architecture

- Apply **SOLID**; favor **high cohesion / low coupling**; use **microservice** boundaries only when requirements justify the operational cost; choose **WebFlux/reactive** vs servlet stack based on team and workload—not by default.
